```javascript
db.shows.insertOne({
  "_id": "show_101",
  "title": "Northern Lights",
  "description": "A crime drama set in Scandinavia.",
  "production_year": 2021,
  "category": "drama",
  "locations": [
    { "name": "Oslo Harbor", "address": "Havnegata 1, Oslo", "latitude": 59.9075, "longitude": 10.7526 }
  ],
  "reviews": [
    { "id": "rev_1", "rating": 4.5, "description": "Gripping and well shot." }
  ],
  "awards": [
    { "id": "awd_1", "type": "Best Drama", "date": "2021-11-20" }
  ],
  "expenses": [
    { "id": "exp_1", "date": "2021-03-05", "type": "services", "amount": 12000, "invoice": "INV-2021-045", "company_name": "CraftCam Ltd." }
  ],
  "script": {
    "id": "scr_1",
    "scriptText": "INT. HARBOR - NIGHT. DETECTIVE LARSEN: 'We found the boat.' ..."
  }
})
```

Each embedded entity (`locations`, `reviews`, `awards`, `expenses`, `script`) appears with its full attribute set at least once, matching the entities and attributes named in the 1.1 ER diagram, and is embedded (rather than referenced) since these sub-objects are always read together with their owning show.

```javascript
db.shows.find({
  "$and": [
    { "production_year": 2021 },
    { "expenses.type": "services" }
  ]
}).limit(5)
```

`expenses.type: "services"` matches any show whose embedded `expenses` array contains at least one element with `type = "services"` (MongoDB implicitly matches array-of-subdocument fields this way). `.limit(5)` caps the result at 5 documents. The `$and` is actually redundant here since MongoDB implicitly ANDs top-level fields — `db.shows.find({production_year: 2021, "expenses.type": "services"}).limit(5)` is equivalent and simpler — but the explicit `$and` form from the exam is also correct.

```javascript
db.shows.aggregate([
  {
    "$project": {
      "title": 1,
      "avg_rating": { "$avg": "$reviews.rating" },
      "num_awards": { "$size": { "$ifNull": ["$awards", []] } }
    }
  },
  {
    "$match": { "avg_rating": { "$gt": 4 } }
  }
])
```

Corrected from the exam transcript: `$group` with `_id: true` would collapse *all* shows into one group, losing the per-show breakdown the question asks for ("...received by **each** show"), and the field references were missing their leading `$` (`"reviews.rating"`/`"awards"` must be `"$reviews.rating"`/`"$awards"` to be evaluated as field paths rather than literal strings), plus the aggregation pipeline array/braces were left unclosed. Using `$project` per-document computes `avg_rating` (average of the embedded `reviews.rating` array) and `num_awards` (size of the embedded `awards` array) for each show individually, then `$match` keeps only shows with `avg_rating > 4`.

```json
PUT reviews
{
  "mappings": {
    "properties": {
      "description": { "type": "text" },
      "rating": { "type": "float" },
      "title": { "type": "keyword" },
      "date": { "type": "date" }
    }
  }
}
```

`description` is `text` so it is analyzed/tokenized for full-text search (needed for 4.3). `rating` is numeric (`float`, since ratings such as 4.5 appear elsewhere in the exam) to support range queries (needed for 4.2). `title` — the "external key" pointing back to the show — is `keyword` (not analyzed) since it is used for exact-match aggregation/terms bucketing, not free-text search.

```json
GET /reviews/_search
{
  "size": 0,
  "query": {
    "bool": {
      "must": {
        "range": { "rating": { "gte": 4 } }
      }
    }
  },
  "aggs": {
    "positive_ratings": {
      "terms": { "field": "title" }
    }
  }
}
```

`size: 0` suppresses the raw hits since only the aggregation result is wanted. The `bool`/`must`/`range` query filters to reviews with `rating >= 4`; the `terms` aggregation on the `title` keyword field then buckets and counts the surviving (positive) reviews per show.

```json
GET /reviews/_search
{
  "query": {
    "match": {
      "description": "good"
    }
  }
}
```

A `match` query on `description` (which must be mapped as `text` so it goes through an analyzer) performs full-text search for the term "good". Elasticsearch's `_search` endpoint already returns hits sorted by descending `_score` (the default relevance/BM25 ranking) unless an explicit `sort` is supplied, so no extra sort clause is needed to satisfy "ordered by return score".
